native language of Greenland has very few vowels. Ranging from 2-4, all of these vowels exist in the English language. However, they are without the majority of the most common ones in our own language like the [ə], [æ], and [ɔ]. One of the first observations that can be made from this data, is that the Greenlandic vowels are primarily on the 4 distinct corners of the vowel chart. These being the most easily discernible: front vs back, and close vs open. %0a%3c %0a%3c Before concluding, I would like to establish several hypotheses for the differences in these two languages. Obviously, English has been around for a long time, and also been a heavy factor in colonization around the world. Therefore, it is not surprising that the greenlandic language has no different vowels than english, rather fewer. My guess would be that time and population size are the greatest factors involved. Finally, I am curious about the effects that climate has on language. How much of an impact did this play in Greenland? Or the contrary, in countries closer to the equator?%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
